<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-136-100 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 813 610</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  June 3 1991 v37 n1863 p37(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Ask high court to alter CPU marketing ruling. (U.S. Department ofJustice appeals to Supreme Court)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gannon, Virginia.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Dept of Justice asks the Supreme Court to overturn a rulingthat computer manufacturers believe will impose on theirtraditional distribution and marketing practices.andP;  The case,Eastman Kodak Co vs Image Technical Services Inc, involves thelegality of Kodak's refusal to sell replacement parts toindependent service organizations (ISOs).andP;  Kodak does sell partsfor its business copiers and micrographics equipment to buyers whodo not use ISOs.andP;  The case was dismissed in trial court in 1990,but the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals reversed that decision.andO;The Justice Dept, which believes that Kodak should be able to sellparts to whomever it chooses, would like the Supreme Court todismiss the case.andP;  If the lower court ruling stands, the JusticeDept believes, companies will not be able to legally devisemarketing strategies to appeal to their customers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Eastman Kodak Co. (Cases).andO;Topic:     Legal IssuesMarketingComputer industryDistribution ManagementUnited States. Department of JusticeUnited States. Supreme CourtCustomer RelationsReplacement Policy.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>